generalExpermnt: I was very engaged during the task, and stopped several times to come up with a hypothesis which I could test for predicting Wilson's behavior. Unfortunately, I found it very difficult to predict Wilson's behavior and it seemed like there were too many variables. I liked that the task was a puzzle and that there was a bonus attached to getting the puzzle correct. I didn't like that I could figure out Wilson's behavior. I didn't find anything odd.
generalStrategy: I considered how much money the stranger put in the bag, what the multiplier of the bag actually was, whether the stranger seemed happy or sad, how much money they had leftover after they gave money to Wilson, how much money they thought Wilson had gotten. Then I tried to see how often each of those variables affected how much money Wilson gave. For example, I learned that when the multiplier was only 2, Wilson did not give any money, and he was much more likely to give money when the multiplier was 6.
generalWilson: Wilson is a bit of a jerk, greedy, and kind of stupid. At the very least he should give people back the money they invested. In many cases, he just took all the strangers' money and kept it. This is not only socially unacceptable (perhaps morally as well), it is bad business practice. If Wilson wants people to keep giving him money, he should return people's investments, especially since he is making money basically for free.
